---
description: 
alwaysApply: true
---

- The body of methods should be decently documented via comments as to facilitate reading.

- Any exceptions to the rules below should be documented directly in the code via comments.

- When designing new code snippets, use a fail fast and loud approach. The code shouldn't have fallbacks that cover up a caller's expected contract breaches.

- A snippet of code should generally be extracted to it's own private / protected method only if it is has >1 usage. Use of private / protected methods as a form of documentation is usually to be avoided unless explicitly specified and documented. Declaration of <=1 use public methods however is perfectly acceptable and expected.

- The definition of a class is to be structured in this order: nested types -> public data-> private data-> public methods -> private methods -> helper methods. "#region ... #endregion" preprocessor directives are to be used to organize these sections if the class is large.

- Compile time constants data and static readonly data should be public unless otherwise specified and use ALL_CAPS_CASE. Compile time constants and static readonly data should be grouped together in the class' declaration.

- When declaring properties, prefer explicitly initializing them to their default value at declaration for clarity's sake, even if they default to the expected value. Readonly data members initialization: POD should be declared inline, anything that requires code execution should be initialized in the constructor instead.

- Properties and methods should be instance properties and methods unless there's a reason to make them static, which case this should be documented via a comment. Helper methods can be declared as static without justification as long as they are part of the helpers region.

- Record types should be sealed by default unless inheritence is needed, it rules out a set of potential subtle autogenerated comparison bugs.

- Prefer methods over getter only properties for things that compute the return value instead of just returning a private field.

- In comments, do not use the <c> tag as it makes reading of comments in the source file cumbersome.
